SIMPLE: burse
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Burse
<hw>Burse</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>bursa</ets>,
or F. <ets>bourse</ets>. See <er>Bourse</er>, and cf. <er>Bursch</er>,
<er>Purse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A purse; also, a vesicle; a pod;
a hull.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fund or foundation for the maintenance of needy
scholars in their studies; also, the sum given to the
beneficiaries.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>An ornamental case of hold the
corporal when not in use.</def> <rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An exchange, for merchants and bankers, in the
cities of continental Europe. Same as <er>Bourse</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A kind of bazaar.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She says she went to the <qex>burse</qex> for patterns.</q>
<rj><qau>Old Play.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Burseraceae</ent>⟦br⟧
